# Experiment 10: HTTP(S) Load Balancer with Cloud Armor

## Aim
To deploy an HTTP(S) Load Balancer and configure a Cloud Armor security policy to protect backend services from unauthorized access.

---

## Step 0: Initial Setup
1. Open Google Cloud Console
2. Select the correct Project
3. Ensure billing is enabled

---

## Step 1: Create Instance Template

1. Navigate to:
   Compute Engine → Instance Templates → Create Instance Template

2. Enter:
   - Name: lb-template
   - Machine type: e2-micro

3. Enable:
   - Allow HTTP traffic

4. Go to:
   Management → Automation → Startup Script

5. Paste:

```bash
#! /bin/bash
apt-get update -y
apt-get install -y apache2
systemctl start apache2
systemctl enable apache2
Click "Create"

Step 2: Create Managed Instance Group (MIG)
Navigate to:
Compute Engine → Instance Groups → Create Instance Group
Enter:
Name: lb-mig
Instance template: lb-template
Location: Single zone
Zone: us-central1-a
Set:
Minimum instances: 2
Click "Create"

Step 3: Create Health Check
Navigate to:
Compute Engine → Health Checks → Create Health Check
Enter:
Name: http-health-check
Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
Click "Create"

Step 4: Create HTTP Load Balancer
Navigate to:
Network Services → Load Balancing → Create Load Balancer
Select:
HTTP(S) Load Balancing
Internet-facing
Click "Start Configuration"

Step 5: Configure Backend Service
Backend name:
web-backend
Add Backend:
Instance Group: lb-mig
Port: 80
Attach Health Check:
http-health-check
Click "Done"

Step 6: Configure Frontend
Set:
Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
IP: Ephemeral
Click "Done"
Click:
"Create Load Balancer"

Step 7: Create Cloud Armor Policy
Navigate to:
Network Security → Cloud Armor → Create Policy
Enter:
Name: block-policy
Default rule: Allow
Add Rule:
Action: Deny (403)
Source IP: YOUR_IP_TO_BLOCK
Priority: 1000
Click:
"Create"

Step 8: Attach Policy to Backend
Navigate to:
Load Balancing → Backend Services
Select:
web-backend
Click:
"Edit"
Set:
Cloud Armor policy: block-policy
Click:
"Update"

Step 9: Test Load Balancer
Get Load Balancer IP
Open browser:
http://LOAD_BALANCER_IP

✔ Expected:

Apache page loads (allowed access)

Step 10: Test Security Policy
Access from blocked IP

✔ Expected:

HTTP 403 Forbidden

----Shell commands
# 1. Setup Variables
export TEMPLATE_NAME="lb-template"
export MIG_NAME="lb-mig"
export REGION="us-central1"
export ZONE="us-central1-a"
export HEALTH_CHECK="http-health-check"
export BACKEND_SERVICE="web-backend"
export SECURITY_POLICY="block-policy"
export BLOCKED_IP="1.2.3.4" # Replace with an actual IP to test blocking

# 2. Create Instance Template & Managed Instance Group (MIG)
gcloud compute instance-templates create $TEMPLATE_NAME \
    --machine-type=e2-micro \
    --tags=http-server \
    --metadata=startup-script='#! /bin/bash
    apt-get update && apt-get install -y apache2
    echo "Welcome to the Load Balanced Server" > /var/www/html/index.html'

gcloud compute instance-groups managed create $MIG_NAME \
    --template=$TEMPLATE_NAME \
    --size=2 \
    --zone=$ZONE

# 3. Create Health Check & Backend Service
gcloud compute health-checks create http $HEALTH_CHECK --port 80

gcloud compute backend-services create $BACKEND_SERVICE \
    --protocol=HTTP \
    --health-checks=$HEALTH_CHECK \
    --global

gcloud compute backend-services add-backend $BACKEND_SERVICE \
    --instance-group=$MIG_NAME \
    --instance-group-zone=$ZONE \
    --global

# 4. Create URL Map, Target Proxy, and Forwarding Rule (Frontend)
gcloud compute url-maps create web-map --default-service=$BACKEND_SERVICE

gcloud compute target-http-proxies create http-proxy --url-map=web-map

gcloud compute forwarding-rules create http-content-rule \
    --load-balancing-scheme=EXTERNAL \
    --address-region=global \
    --target-http-proxy=http-proxy \
    --ports=80

# 5. Create Cloud Armor Policy and Rules
gcloud compute security-policies create $SECURITY_POLICY \
    --description="Block specific IP and allow others"

gcloud compute security-policies rules create 1000 \
    --security-policy=$SECURITY_POLICY \
    --expression="inIpRange(origin.ip, '$BLOCKED_IP')" \
    --action="deny-403" \
    --description="Deny access to specific IP"

# 6. Attach Policy to Backend Service
gcloud compute backend-services update $BACKEND_SERVICE \
    --security-policy=$SECURITY_POLICY \
    --global

# 7. Verification - Get the Load Balancer IP
echo "Wait a few minutes for the Load Balancer to initialize..."
gcloud compute forwarding-rules describe http-content-rule --global --format="value(IPAddress)"
